      <div class="space-y-3" id="faq-list">
        <div class="accordion-item">
          <button class="accordion-trigger faq-trigger">
            What hydration is best for beginners?
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-5 w-5 transition-transform faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
              <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.293 7.293a1 1 0 011.414 0L10 10.586l3.293-3.293a1 1 0 111.414 1.414l-4 4a1 1 0 01-1.414 0l-4-4a1 1 0 010-1.414z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
            </svg>
          </button>
          <div class="accordion-content hidden">
            Start with 65-70% hydration. Lower hydration doughs are easier to handle and shape. As you gain experience, gradually increase to 75-80% for more open crumb.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="accordion-item">
          <button class="accordion-trigger faq-trigger">
            Can I use all-purpose flour instead of bread flour?
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-5 w-5 transition-transform faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
              <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.293 7.293a1 1 0 011.414 0L10 10.586l3.293-3.293a1 1 0 111.414 1.414l-4 4a1 1 0 01-1.414 0l-4-4a1 1 0 010-1.414z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
            </svg>
          </button>
          <div class="accordion-content hidden">
            Yes, but reduce hydration by 3-5%. All-purpose flour has less protein (10-12% vs 12-14% for bread flour), so it absorbs less water and produces a slightly softer crumb.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="accordion-item">
          <button class="accordion-trigger faq-trigger">
            Why is my bread dense?
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-5 w-5 transition-transform faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
              <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.293 7.293a1 1 0 011.414 0L10 10.586l3.293-3.293a1 1 0 111.414 1.414l-4 4a1 1 0 01-1.414 0l-4-4a1 1 0 010-1.414z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
            </svg>
          </button>
          <div class="accordion-content hidden">
            Common causes: underproofed dough (not enough fermentation time), weak/inactive starter, cold dough temperature, or not enough gluten development. Try longer bulk ferment and ensure your starter passes the float test.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="accordion-item">
          <button class="accordion-trigger faq-trigger">
            Why use baker's percentages?
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-5 w-5 transition-transform faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
              <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.293 7.293a1 1 0 011.414 0L10 10.586l3.293-3.293a1 1 0 111.414 1.414l-4 4a1 1 0 01-1.414 0l-4-4a1 1 0 010-1.414z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
            </svg>
          </button>
          <div class="accordion-content hidden">
            Baker's percentages make scaling recipes easy and allow you to compare recipes at a glance. All ingredients are expressed as a percentage of the flour weight (flour is always 100%), so you can instantly see hydration, salt level, and other ratios.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="accordion-item">
          <button class="accordion-trigger faq-trigger">
            Do I need a Dutch oven?
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-5 w-5 transition-transform faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
              <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.293 7.293a1 1 0 011.414 0L10 10.586l3.293-3.293a1 1 0 111.414 1.414l-4 4a1 1 0 01-1.414 0l-4-4a1 1 0 010-1.414z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
            </svg>
          </button>
          <div class="accordion-content hidden">
            Not required, but highly recommended for home ovens. It traps steam, giving you the crispy crust and oven spring that's hard to achieve otherwise. Alternatives: baking stone with steam pan, or inverted roasting pan.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
